<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">React is a JavaScript
library aimed for front-end development to build user interfaces. It takes care
of what is displayed to the user and how they interact with our application.
React is designed in a way so when the data in your app changes, the user
interface will automatically update too, without the need to worry about
manually updating the DOM.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="MsoNormal">

<!--StartFragment-->

<p class="MsoNormal">An application using
React, could be built from a series of reusable <i>components</i>. <i>Components</i> can
represent any part of our user interface. For example, if we’re looking to
create a competitor for Google Maps, you might have a <span style="font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Menlo;background:#E7E6E6;mso-shading-themecolor:
background2;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">Map</span> component for viewing the map, and a <span style="font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Menlo;background:#E7E6E6;mso-shading-themecolor:
background2;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">LocationInput</span> component that would allow our users to
enter a location.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">We can note that every tag (like: html, head, body & div) must have
a starting tag: <code>< name ></code> and a closing tag: <code></ name ></code>. The closing
tag differs from the start tag’s declaration by including a forward slash right
after the starting less-than `<code> </</code> `.</span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB"><br></span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">In Web-Development, any HTML DOM element can either be declared directly in the HTML document, or created through JavaScript:</span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB"><br></span></p>

<!--EndFragment-->
var ele = document.createElement("div");ele.className = "someClassName";ele.innerText = "Body Contents";document.getElementsByTagName("body")[0].append( ele );

EN-GB">As we can see in the above example, we are creating an element, then we
assigned its class name, given it some contents and finally appended it on the
DOM. It is evident that it needs more code to create the same element result
through JavaScript, and that’s why React gave us the ability to use the same
syntax:<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<h2><b><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">The DOM</span></b></h2>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">The DOM (or, Document Object Model) is kinda abstract, because it is
what the browser use internally to structure our web-applications. The DOM
isn’t just the HTML, and to get a good visual representation of what the DOM
looks like, we need to open up the browser’s Dev Tools and look for the
Elements tab. That visual structure (which closely resembles the HTML) is a
fairly good representation of a DOM. React creates its own DOM!<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">To allow our apps to render efficiently, React uses a technology called
the <i>virtual DOM</i>. The <i>virtual DOM</i> stores a copy of our
current DOM in memory. When our app's data changes, it calculates which parts
of the DOM need to be refreshed (re-rendered / repainted / altered), and only
updates these elements. This makes UI built with React, updates very quickly,
even for large, complex apps.</span></p><p class="MsoNormal">

<!--EndFragment--></p><p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">Before we start to get to know React, it is important to understand a
couple of prerequisites (dependencies) that React needs in order to function
properly. In JavaScript, the greater-than (</span><span style="font-size:10.0pt;
font-family:Menlo;color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;background:#E7E6E6;
mso-shading-themecolor:background2;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"><code> < > </code></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">) and
smaller-than symbols used in XML are only acceptable in conditions. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">So how React doesn’t collide with JavaScript when it is in fact
JavaScript in itself?! This question brings us to explore a library called
Babel. The Babel “<i style="mso-bidi-font-style:normal">transpiler</i>” (<i style="mso-bidi-font-style:normal">aka transcompiler, takes code written in a
certain language, or version of a language, and converts it into valid code in
a different language</i>) takes any XML and outputs it in plain JavaScript
syntax. To better understand this in action, we need to visit: <span style="mso-tab-count:1">            </span></span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US"><span lang="EN-GB" style="mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"><a href="https://babeljs.io/repl">https://babeljs.io/repl</a></span></span><span style="color: black;"> </span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">Babel is also responsible for future JavaScript versions (as per ECMA
standards) that aren’t yet standard in all major browser vendors, and outputs
as plain JavaScript in default version (ES5).</span></p><p class="MsoNormal">

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">With the help of the above JSXTransformer, our JavaScript with XML
becomes acceptable. You can also come across files ending `</span><span style="font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Menlo;color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;
mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"><code>*.jsx</code></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:
text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">` instead of `</span><span style="font-size:
10.0pt;font-family:Menlo;color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB"><code>*.js</code></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">` to help certain environments differentiate how to deal with such
files.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">The other prerequisite for React is Webpack. Webpack is a very vast and
complex library, that helps development with React a breeze. Webpack nowadays
became quite difficult to categorize under one category, like bundler, because
due to the open source community, many plugins were created for it, which also
became staple, that now Webpack (with Babel plugins amongst the plethora
available) gives us a build system. </span></p>

<h1></h1><div><hr><br></div><h1><b><span style="color: black;"><u>Anatomy of a Build System</u></span></b></h1>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB"> </span><span style="color: black;">Front-end development has become more and more sophisticated, with an
ecosystem of tools which has grown to allow us to process our code and assets
before running or deploying them. For example, there are tools that allow us
to:</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"></p><ul><li><span style="text-indent: -18pt; color: black;"><span style="font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: 'Times New Roman';"> </span></span><span style="text-indent: -18pt; color: black;">Translate ES6
JavaScript to ES5 so it can work on older browsers</span><br></li><li><span style="text-indent: -18pt; color: black;"><span style="font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: 'Times New Roman';"> </span></span><span style="text-indent: -18pt; color: black;">Shrink the
size of our JavaScript and CSS code so they are served to users more quickly</span><br></li><li><span style="color: black; text-indent: -18pt;">Automatically
compress images to save bandwidth</span><br></li><li><span style="text-indent: -18pt; color: black;"><span style="font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: 'Times New Roman';"> </span></span><span style="text-indent: -18pt; color: black;">Add new
features and syntax to make CSS easier to write</span></li></ul>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">With so many tools available we have a new problem. Although we can run
the tools manually this quickly becomes a burden, especially when we need to
rerun the tools every time we change some code.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB"> </span><span style="color: black;">Build systems are pieces of software designed to help with this
coordination; they are responsible for building our code so that it is ready to
be run or deployed.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB"> </span><span style="color: black;">Loqus has its preferred build system which is based on NPM</span></p>

<!--EndFragment-->

<h2><b><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">NPM as a build
system</span></b></h2><div><font color="#000000">The build system is based on a series of NPM scripts, each of which performs a certain task to build our code. The scripts are declared in the <code>scripts</code> section of the <code>package.json</code> file. For example, a <code>package.json</code> file might have the following <code>scripts</code> section:</font></div>

<!--EndFragment-->
..."scripts": {  "build": "webpack",  "test": "mocha"}...

<h2><b><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">Babel</span></b></h2>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">As mentioned above, Babel is the JavaScript transpiler used by our build
system. For our React applications, it will play two roles:</span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst" style="text-indent:-18.0pt;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo1"></p><ul><li><span style="text-indent: -18pt; color: black;">Taking code
written using ES6 syntax, and converting it into code that is compatible with
ES5</span><br></li><li>Convert
React’s JSX syntax into plain JavaScript code<br></li></ul><!--[if !supportLists]--><p></p>



<!--EndFragment-->

<!--StartFragment-->

<h2><b><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">Webpack</span></b></h2>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">As briefly described above, we’ll be using Webpack as our module
bundler. It will take our code split across multiple files and bundles it into
a single file.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">Webpack uses either ES6 modules (using </span><span style="font-size:10.5pt;font-family:Menlo;color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;
background:#E7E6E6;mso-shading-themecolor:background2;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"><code>import</code></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> and </span><span style="font-size:10.5pt;font-family:Menlo;color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;
background:#E7E6E6;mso-shading-themecolor:background2;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"><code>export</code></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">) or <i>CommonJS</i> modules (using </span><span style="font-size:10.5pt;font-family:Menlo;color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;
background:#E7E6E6;mso-shading-themecolor:background2;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"><code>module.exports</code></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> and </span><span style="font-size:10.5pt;font-family:Menlo;color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;
background:#E7E6E6;mso-shading-themecolor:background2;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"><code>require</code></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">) to work out
which files need to be included in the bundle. We specify a single file as an
entry point. Any files which are imports by our entry point are included in the
bundle. Then any files which are imported by the newly added files are also
included, and this continues recursively until all of our code is packaged up
in a single file.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB"> </span><span style="color: black;">Webpack is also responsible for coordinating the processing of the
files. This means that it is webpack's job to run the JavaScript files which it
finds through Babel before adding them to the bundle. </span></p>

<!--EndFragment-->

<h1><hr></h1><h1><b><span style="color: black;"><u>Primer on ES6</u></span></b></h1>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">Most developers find writing React code in ES6 a nicer experience, and
most of the documentation around React takes advantage of ES6.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">We’ll be going over some ES6 features that are commonly used in React
apps. Specifically, we’ll cover:</span></p>

<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst" style="text-indent:-18.0pt;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo1"></p><ul><li><span style="text-indent: -18pt; color: black;"><span style="font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: 'Times New Roman';"> </span></span><span style="text-indent: -18pt; color: black;">how </span><span style="text-indent: -18pt; font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Menlo; color: black; background-color: rgb(231, 230, 230); background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;">this</span><span style="text-indent: -18pt; color: black;"> works with
arrow functions</span><br></li><li><span style="text-indent: -18pt; color: black;"><span style="font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: 'Times New Roman';"> </span></span><span style="text-indent: -18pt; color: black;">object
destructuring</span><br></li><li><span style="text-indent: -18pt; color: black;"><span style="font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: 'Times New Roman';"> </span></span><span style="text-indent: -18pt; color: black;">property value
shorthand</span><br></li><li><span style="text-indent: -18pt; color: black;"><span style="font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: 'Times New Roman';"> </span></span><span style="text-indent: -18pt; color: black;">the spread
operator</span><br></li><li><span style="text-indent: -18pt; font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Menlo; color: black;"><span style="font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: 'Times New Roman';"> </span></span><span style="text-indent: -18pt; font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: Menlo; color: black; background-color: rgb(231, 230, 230); background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;">Object.assign</span><br></li><li><span style="text-indent: -18pt; color: black;"><span style="font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: 'Times New Roman';"> </span></span><span style="text-indent: -18pt; color: black;">modules,
imports and exports</span><br></li><li><span style="text-indent: -18pt; color: black;"><span style="font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-family: 'Times New Roman';"> </span></span><span style="text-indent: -18pt; color: black;">classes</span></li></ul>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">For more in-depth coverage of ES6, please visit this </span><span lang="EN-US"><a href="https://hacks.mozilla.org/category/es6-in-depth/"><span lang="EN-GB">set of articles</span></a></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">For each of the following language features, we provide examples of
usage and a description of the use cases for the feature.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<!--StartFragment-->

<h2><b><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">Lexical </span></b><span style="font-size:10.5pt;font-family:Menlo;color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;
background:#E7E6E6;mso-shading-themecolor:background2;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">this</span><b><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:
text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> with arrow functions</span></b><span style="color: black; font-size: 13px;"> </span></h2>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">If you’ve done any client-side programming in ES5, you’ve probably dealt
with bugs in your code caused by </span><span style="font-size:10.5pt;
font-family:Menlo;color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;background:#E7E6E6;
mso-shading-themecolor:background2;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"><code>this</code></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> acting in
counterintuitive ways. With ES6’s </span><span lang="EN-US"><a href="https://strongloop.com/strongblog/an-introduction-to-javascript-es6-arrow-functions/"><span lang="EN-GB">arrow functions</span></a></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">, </span><span style="font-size:10.5pt;font-family:Menlo;color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;
background:#E7E6E6;mso-shading-themecolor:background2;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"><code>this</code></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> behaves more
consistently, and on top of that, we get a more succinct syntax for declaring
functions:<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<!--EndFragment-->

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">Note how the </span><span style="font-size:10.5pt;font-family:Menlo;
color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;background:#E7E6E6;mso-shading-themecolor:
background2;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"><code>function</code></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> keyword is omitted.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">The </span><span style="font-size:10.5pt;color:black;mso-themecolor:
text1;background:#E7E6E6;mso-shading-themecolor:background2;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB"><code>return</code></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB"> command is <i>sometimes</i> omitted
with arrow functions. For single line function bodies like the one above,
return statements aren’t required.</span><span style="color: black;"> </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">For multi-line function bodies, </span><span style="font-size:10.5pt;
font-family:Menlo;color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;background:#E7E6E6;
mso-shading-themecolor:background2;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"><code>{...}</code></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> curly
brackets are used, and </span><span style="font-size:10.5pt;font-family:Menlo;
color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;background:#E7E6E6;mso-shading-themecolor:
background2;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"><code>return</code></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> is required (if the function is
meant to explicitly return a value)<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<h2><b><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"><br></span></b></h2><h2><b><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">Object
destructuring assignment</span></b></h2>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US"><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Destructuring_assignment"><span lang="EN-GB">Destructuring assignment</span></a></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> is a new way
of assigning values contained in Objects and Arrays, to new variables.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">In this Introduction to React, we will use <i>object destructuring</i>:<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<!--EndFragment-->

<!--StartFragment-->

<h2><b><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">Property value shorthand</span></b></h2>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">This is a convenient shorthand we can use when we need to create an
object literal out of a set of variables, and we want to map variable names to
keys. It is essentially the inverse of object destructuring.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<!--EndFragment-->

<h2><b><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB"><br></span></b></h2><h2><b><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">Spread operator</span></b><span style="color: black;"> </span></h2>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">The </span><span lang="EN-US"><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Spread_operator" target="_blank"><span lang="EN-GB">spread
operator</span></a></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;
mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> provides a compact way to apply parameters to
functions.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<!--EndFragment-->
The spread operator can also be used to copy contents of one Array elsewhere:

Object.assign 

The Object.assign method helps us manage merging Objects, and we’ll use it throughout this introduction. Properties from objects passed as the 2nd, 3rd, 4th, etc. arguments are merged into the object passed as the first argument. Properties of later arguments will overwrite properties with the same name from earlier arguments, like so:

Modules

Modules allow us to split our code into multiple files, exporting objects from one file and importing them into another. Each module provides a single object for importing, which we can destructure to access the individual variables that were exported, like:

background2;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">class</span><span style="color:black;

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">Classes have a constructor method that is used to set any initial
properties of an object created from the class. The constructor is called when
the class is <i>instantiated</i>.
Instantiating a class creates a new Object that has all of the methods of the
class.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">To instantiate a class we use the </span><span style="font-size:10.5pt;
font-family:Menlo;color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;background:#E7E6E6;
mso-shading-themecolor:background2;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">new</span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> keyword:<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">The </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Dog</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> class is a
more specific version of the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:
10.5pt"><code>Animal</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;
mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> class. Note how the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Dog</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:
text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> constructor calls the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>super</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> method. </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>super</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> calls the constructor of the
parent class. In this case the parent class of </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Dog</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:
text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> is </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Animal</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">, so </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>super</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> calls the constructor of the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Animal</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> class.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">The call to </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>super</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> is needed to
delegate the initialization of the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>name</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:
text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> property to the parent class. This means that
we don’t need to repeat </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>this.name
= name;</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB"> in both the parent and child class.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">The child class ( </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Dog</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> ) overrides
the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>speak</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> method from
the parent class. We have two types of Object ( </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Dog</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:
text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> and </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Animal</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> ) which share an <i>interface</i> (i.e.: they both have a </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>speak</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> method with
the same call signature), but have a different implementation. This is known as
<i>polymorphism</i>.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

React Components

React applications are made up of components. You can think of components as the building blocks of our applications.

For example, take the application you’re using to follow this course in. If you had to rewrite it using React, the top menu bar might be one component. The content of what you’re actually read now could be another component. And if any side-bars are needed/visible, that could be a 3rd component. The components would be reusable. The same body-content component would display a different course, depending whether you were studying the Introduction to React curriculum or the Advanced React curriculum. 

The components themselves work by rendering a number of HTML elements. Let’s dive in code to see how this works by first cloning this repo: 

git clone https://github.com/pixelwashacademy/loqus-react.git 

for this application, we’re going to use a simple and basic setup to work with React. We’re loading the Babel transpiler directly in the HTML document (through the JSXTransformer.js module). This is going to be our boilerplate to start from. All remote files will be delivered through CDNs (Content Delivery Network).

The HTML document ( index.html ) contains all needed files:

  • We’re loading Twitter’s Bootstrap, to help us with some styling and keeping the style of our app consistent throughout any browser used.
  • We’re loading some custom CSS style to make our example-project looks like Trello
  • We’re loading the React library, version 15.3.2
  • We also need React’s DOM, to render our components in the browser
  • The JSX Transformer is loaded right after React’s library
  • And last but not least, our JavaScript file ( script.js ) in which we’ll code the necessary components.

After carrying out the above cloning step, we can see 3 files (4, including the README.md), index.html, script.js & style.css

If the above is correct, take a good look at this setup, list any questions you might have (to ask your mentor during the next mentor-session) and we can now start creating some React components! 

Let’s first jump into the relevant branch for this step:

            git checkout components

The above step will update our script.js file with a simple stateless component, through a function, which is returning XML.

You can also visit the pull requests for comments and such, here:

https://github.com/PixelWashAcademy/loqus-react/pull/1

Components

As we saw from this first example, simple React components can be created through a JS function. This is not always possible, in cases where we need to store any data inside a component. In such cases, we’ll use the Component class from the React library. In our next example, we’re going to first “translate” our function component in a React Component. We start by changing into the next branch: 

            git checkout props

Properties (aka props)

In React, properties are known as props and these are frequently used. We can pass props to a component from a “parent” component. Like we’ve seen in the earlier example, we can use any HTML element in our React components, and, we can also use other React components in our components! A parent component can then pass any props to a child component. In this example, although the ReactDOM isn’t an actual component, it is serving as one, because there’s nothing higher than the ReactDOM in React’s hierarchy.

 As we can see in the code, our function changed into a class. Like we discussed in the ES6 Primer earlier, we can extend from an existent class (being the React Component class) and then add our own. In these components we need to declare a render method, which will be automatically called by React, to render in DOM whatever we return from it. 

We can see that our h2 element’s content is now different, in which we are using curly braces (aka curly brackets – { } ). These braces tell React that this should be interpreted as JavaScript. The braces are a means to “escape” JavaScript in regular text. Furthermore, we are referring to this.props which means any properties passed to this component. this.props.title will be then passed a value through the title prop, such as:
<ComponentName title="some title" />

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">The most important fact to remember about “passing props” is to imagine
a data-channel between 2 components, through which we can pass any form of data
(variables, methods, etc). Usually, a parent component passes data (over props)
to a child component, but we can also send from a child to a parent. Take a
good look at the below example and please let us know if you have any
questions:<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<!--EndFragment-->

<p class="MsoNormal"><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>children</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> are available
in props inherently, so unlike “plain” </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>props</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">, in which we can use the most
semantic label as we wish (like, </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>this.props.title</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> or </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>this.props.user</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">), </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">children</span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> are called and found as:<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"><code>this.props.children</code></span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">We can say that </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">children</span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> are a
property of </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">props</span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">. Let’s jump
into our next branch to see this:</span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB"><span style="mso-spacerun:yes"> </span><span style="mso-tab-count:1">           </span></span><span style="font-size:10.5pt;font-family:Menlo;color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;
background:#E7E6E6;mso-shading-themecolor:background2;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">git
checkout children</span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">In this part we can see some changes. So far we’ve passed multiple
components directly to the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>ReactDOM.render</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> method,
wrapped in a </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>div</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> tag. Albeit
functional, GPP (Good Programming Practices) dictates that we should create a
separate component to hold in all needed components. Kind of the skeleton of
our React app. This is a better practice for us humans to be able to read the
code easily.</span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">First, we can see that our component changed its </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>h3</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> tag to a
paragraph </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code><p></code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> tag. In this
element we provided the necessary link to React to deal with any children
passed on later, through: </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>this.props.children</code></span></span><span style="color: black;"> </span></p><p class="MsoNormal">

<!--StartFragment-->

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">We also created a hook for the DOM element </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>content</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> so we can pass this variable to </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>ReactDOM</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: black;">Before moving onto the next step, let’s pass another </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Trello</code></span></span><span style="color: black;"> component to
our </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Layout</code></span></span><span style="color: black;"> and in the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>title</code></span></span><span style="color: black;"> </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>props</code></span></span><span style="color: black;"> let’s pass
HTML elements to see how it works.</span></p>

<!--EndFragment-->

<Trello title={ <button className="btn-primary">Prop</button> } user="David">
  children text
</Trello>
and this should get our Layout component to look this this:

function Layout(props) { return (
children as dud-button text Prop } user="David"> children text
) }

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">Note that now the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>title</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> property’s
value isn’t a String ( </span><code>"John"</code><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> ) but it’s
starting with curly braces to prompt React that we’re passing JavaScript or
JSX.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<!--EndFragment-->

Events

Events in React are largely the same as the ones found in the browser’s native DOM. The only difference is how they are referred to (left native – right React):

onclick         ===       onClick
                  onmouseenter    ===       onMouseEnter
                  onscroll        ===       onScroll
                  defaultvalue    ===       defaultValue

EN-GB">            </span><span style="font-size:10.5pt;font-family:Menlo;color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;
background:#E7E6E6;mso-shading-themecolor:background2;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">git
checkout events</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">Here we can see that we’ve attached an </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>onClick</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> event-listener to the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>p</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> tag, and when
it’s triggered, it is calling the method declared within the same component
named </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>clicker</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><i><u><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">A note on
comments in JSX</span></u></i><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;
mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">: like you might have already noticed, comments inside
JSX are not the “conventional” double forward-slash ( </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>//</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:
text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> ) as these are a bit more laborious with an
opening for the comment and another for the closing:<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>{ /*  and comments needed */ }</code><o:p></o:p></span></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">JSX comments are wrapped in curly braces, to inform Babel that we’re
“escaping” normal declarations. Then we continue with a more “traditional”
kind, with a forward-slash followed by an asterisk to open the
comment-statement, and an asterisk followed by a forward-slash to close it.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

Event Handling

After dealing with events (event listeners) now it’s time to do something with them. In the previous example, we saw how the onClick event listener was calling the clicker method. Let’s start giving some shape to our Trello-like application.

First we need to jump into the relevant branch:

            git checkout event-handling

At this stage, we’re going to be able to give “life” to our applications, by having our users interact with it. Let’s do some house-cleaning of our code, and give a look to our new script.js file.

We can see that our Trello component received two methods, which they are being invoked on the buttons onClick listener. Although at the moment these 2 methods are simply logging out text to the console (via console.log) they will make more sense soon. When a component is loaded on the DOM, its render method is invoked automatically by React. If we need to call the render method again, to pass different elements or data, React has a very powerful architecture that helps us in doing that. Will be covering this in the next step.

Please note, that React (version 15 onwards) event-handlers, and any invoked methods, must be through a function. In earlier versions of React, we could have just said:
<element onClick={this.methodName}>

State

State is React’s biggest “selling point”. What is state after all?! State is a JavaScript Object, in any React.Component that we can store any needed data in it. The JS Object was chosen for its versatility because we can store any needed data-type:

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">As we can see, </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>this.state</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> is an </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Object</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">, and like any
JS Object, its key/value pairs can be whatever we need. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">We already mentioned that the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>render</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> method in a </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>React.Component</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> is
automatically invoked once the component is loaded in the DOM, and, it keeps
getting invoked every time there’s any change to the state. The most popular
example to demonstrate this, needs a particular and very simple Component.
Let’s start by switching the branch of our repo:</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">            </span><span style="font-size:10.5pt;font-family:Menlo;color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;
background:#E7E6E6;mso-shading-themecolor:background2;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">git
checkout state</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">The </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Counter</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> component is
declaring state with a key/value of </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>num: 0</code></span></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">In each of the declared methods (</span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>increase</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> & </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>decrease</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">) we are changing/mutating the
value of </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>num</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">, and since </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>num</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> is within our
state’s “<i>confines</i>” this will trigger
a call to the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>render</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> method. This
is the simplest example to show how re-render occurs once state changes. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">The two buttons are “listening” for mouse-clicks through the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>onClick</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> event, and
when this is triggered, they are calling their respective methods. Both methods
are changing the state, hence re-render occurs.</span></p>

Adding State to Components

After following the previous example (i.e.: re-render on state change), let’s jump back to our Trello-like application, and decide what state it needs.

First checkout the branch needed:

            git checkout adding-state

In our script.js we can notice a drastic change from our previous version of the Trello component. Each note or comment (or trello) has 2 distinct states. In one state it is displaying the contents of note, and in the other state, it is receiving the contents of the note.

So we said that state could be either { editing: true } or { editing: false }.

We also created the respective methods that will be called to change the state, edit() & save()

The most important point to observe here, is how the render method is returning elements to the DOM. Every time the render is invoked, it first checks if this.state.editing is either true or false, and according to that condition, it then invokes its corresponding method, either renderNormal or renderForm, in which these rendering methods take care of returning/displaying the appropriate elements.

At the moment, when a user tries changing the contents of the note, it is being ignored, because we’re not yet addressing that step. How we would go about, extracting data from user inputs? Let’s get to it.

Refs

refs are only available within React, and such attribute is not found on native HTML elements. FaceBook created refs to give us direct access to user inputs through the same library, rather than having to go back to JavaScript for DOM manipulation. It is interesting how refs are used and declared, because within the element, we use ref (singular) and when we need to access that given element’s reference, we call them by this.refs 

Let’s jump in, and first run:

            git checkout refs

Now we can see 2 changes.

The first one is in the <textarea> element in which we’ve added the ref attribute of “newText”:
<textarea ref=”newText”>
The second is in the save() method, in which we are accessing the value inserted in the textarea:
const val = this.refs.newText.value;

For now, we are only printing ( console.log ) the text extracted from the textarea into the JavaScript Console in the browser’s Dev Tools. We are not actually saving the new text for now, because first we need to change how our application is designed! We are passing the default value of each note as children, which is not akin to the proper implementation for such an app. We need a parent component to hold the contents of each note, and pass the data to and from a child component.

Multiple Child Components

Instead of using a Layout skeleton for only appending our Trello components on the DOM, let’s make better use of it, and we’ll start by changing it from a stateless component ( function ) to a stateful one ( React.Component )

            git checkout child-components

On this step, we have separated, and also delegated our concerns. In the Layout component we are storing each note’s contents, and depending on how many comments are in this component’s state, its respective Trello note will be mapped over. We can see on line 75 that the state is getting mapped, and through each iteration, we are creating a new Trello for that iteration’s value.
this.state.comments     ===     [ “Note 1”, “Note 2”, “Note 3” ]

<p class="MsoNormal"><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Array</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">s are
“iterable” and the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>map</code></span></span>
<span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">method
returns a new </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Array</code></span></span>
<span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">containing
whatever we instruct it to. We also added a </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>key</code></span></span> <span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:
text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">attribute to the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Trello</code></span></span> <span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">component and this is something
required by design in React. When we “feed” an “iterable” variable (like the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>map</code></span></span> <span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">method
generates), each generated element/component should contain a unique </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>key</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">. We are using
the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Array</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">’s indices to
pass on that unique value for each iterated element: </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>[ 0, 1, 2 ]</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt">If this <code>map</code> method looks weird, we can go over it through the more verbose ES5:</span></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">The </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>map</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> method’s
callback function takes 2 arguments/parameters. The 1<sup>st</sup> argument is
for the value it finds on each iteration, and the 2<sup>nd</sup> argument will
be the index of that given element within the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Array</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">. In this step we used both, as
we need the contents to pass as </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:
10.5pt"><code>children</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;
mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> to the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Trello</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> component, and the index for the
</span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>key</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> uniqueness.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<!--EndFragment-->

Updating State and Removing Components

In the previous step, we changed our initial “architecture” of our app, as now the Layout component is responsible for each note’s (Trello) contents, as well as where it resides in the Array indices. From this point onwards, our Layout component will keep growing, and since it isn’t used anymore as a “scaffold” to prop up our components on the DOM, we should think about moving it to its own file. Let’s start by doing some house-cleaning, and divide our current script.js into 2 smaller files: Trello.js and Layout.js. Since we are not developing our small app through a build environment (as we’ll be covering this later on in the course), we need this change in our file/s to be reflected in our HTML document. Just like JavaScript, which is interpreted/read from left to right, top to bottom, HTML is parsed in the same way. In our Layout component, we are calling the Trello component, so the Trello.js file must be loaded before we load our Layout.js file, otherwise we’ll encounter a Reference Error, that Trello is undefined!

Before we jump into the next branch, first please take a good look at the Layout component render method, Line 75, specifically the map’s callback:
this.state.comments.map(( text,i ) => ( <Trello key={i}>{text}</Trello> ))

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">            </span><span style="font-size:10.5pt;font-family:Menlo;color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;
background:#E7E6E6;mso-shading-themecolor:background2;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">git
checkout updating-state</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">In </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Layout</code></span></span>
<span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">component
we can find the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>mapTrello</code></span></span>
<span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">method,
which took place in the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>map</code></span></span>
<span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">callback.
If you’re not familiar with JavaScript, you might find it weird that the
arguments aren’t passed. This is done implicitly by JavaScript, by </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>bind</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">ing the
callback to the method, and any arguments are passed automatically. This
example might shed more light:<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><i><span style="color:red;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">It is very important to note, that
according to React’s documentation and guidelines, it is not possible for React
to </span></i><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>bind</code></span></span><i><span style="color:red;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB"> methods when passed as </span></i><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>props</code></span></span><i><span style="color:red;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">, and in such case, we cannot rely on
the implicit </span></i><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>bind</code></span></span><i><span style="color:red;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">ing as it won’t work. Implicit </span></i><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>bind</code></span></span><i><span style="color:red;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">ing only works with absolute
variables. To pass </span></i><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>function</code></span></span><i><span style="color:red;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">s (i.e.: methods) we need to pass any necessary arguments. The TL;DR of
this concept is that </span></i><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>function</code></span></span><i><span style="color:red;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">s can make use of the </span></i><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>this</code></span></span><i><span style="color:red;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> keyword and using implicit </span></i><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>bind</code></span></span><i><span style="color:red;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">ing (from ES5) doesn’t work, and creates unexpected behaviour. If this
is unclear, or you have any questions, thoughts, doubts or concerns, please jot
them all down so you’ll be able to ask your lecturer during sessions</span></i><span style="color:red;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">With the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Layout</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> component
given more “responsibility” we should consider moving other methods to it.
Let’s start by taking the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>remove</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> method. The </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>remove</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> method will
be assigned to each </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Trello</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> component, so
when the user wants to delete that note, they can perfectly do so by clicking
the corresponding UI/button.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">As we’ve pointed out already, the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Layout</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> component is “governing” the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Trello</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> component/s.
In order to remove a </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Trello</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> from the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Layout</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">, and to
update the contents of a </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Trello</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">, we need to
pass on this information/data to the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Layout</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> component. We can imagine that
the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Layout</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> component
needs methods that manipulate its state according to the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Trello</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> UI. How are
we gonna make the two components communicate? We need to pass </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>props</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> from one another, and we’ll see how we can send methods as </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>props</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">, as well as how a child (<i>i.e.:</i> </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Trello</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">) can send </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>props</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> upwards to
its parent (<i>i.e.:</i> </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Layout</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">)</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">In order not to have too much code/changes thrown at you in one go
(which helps in solidifying better your understanding of each step), we’re
gonna do the remove and update in the next step. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

Passing Methods as Props

We need to start by changing our branch to:

            git checkout passing-props

In the Layout component we’ve now added two new methods, the removeNote and the updateNew. As we can see, both of these methods need arguments/parameters that aren’t within the Layout component! So far, we’ve only managed to pass data through props downstream (from parent to child) but now we need the child component to pass data to the parent component. Let’s first take a look at how the mapTrello method is now passing the Layout’s methods to Trello through props:

In Layout.js, in lines 19 – 21 we are “creating new data-channels” (or transmitting frequencies, if you will) as we are passing new props from Layout to Trello. The newly added props are semantically labelled as index, updateToTrello & removeToTrello. This means, that when the Trello component “tunes its frequency onto those channels” it will be able to receive their data. So let’s now look in Trello.js and see how it is actually accessing these new props “channels”.

In this section, both files received significant changes. We are passing the methods inside Layout component to the Trello component. The Trello component is invoking said methods while also passing their necessary arguments. This part of React’s “architecture” is one of the reasons why it garnered so much popularity with developers worldwide.

Layout.js received:

removeTrello()  which takes care of removing the passed index of the given comment in state

updateTrello()  which takes care of updating the passed index & contents of the given comment in state

mapTrello()  which was “refactored” with the mapping being invoked within


Trello.js received:

save()  which now needs an index argument, and was “refactored” so it actually gets the value of the comment in input tag through this.refs, then it passes said value along with the index argument through props on updateToTrello which in return is invoking the updateTrello in Layout. Finally it flips the Trello’s state from editing true to false.

remove()  which now needs an index argument, so it can pass it through props to removeToTrello, which in return invokes the removeTrello in Layout, which splice out that comment from the state’s Array.

renderNormal()  now we are passing the index of the note which is available through this.props.index, to the Trello’s remove method

renderForm()  now we are passing the index of the note which is available through this.props.index, to the Trello’s save method

New Components

We’re at the last step in finishing our small Trello-like application. Some steps were only taken to “illustrate” particular concepts in React. Before getting to the last features of our app, it’s important to point out what are referred to as LifeCycle Methods. These lifecycle methods are built-in React, but these are going to be deprecated on the upcoming major version of this library (v17). Millions of projects and applications have been created using such methods, and apart from the educational importance in covering them, we need to know how these work in order to be able to deal with them in our work at Loqus.

Lifecycle Methods

Let’s start by going over the below table and then we’ll discuss them further:

|Method                  |When is it called?                 |Common Usage               |
|------------------------|-----------------------------------|---------------------------|
|`constructor(props)`    |when the component is initialized  |Setting the initial state  |
|`componentWillMount()`  |when the component is initialized  |None; it is better to use the constructor|
|`componentDidMount()`   |when the componnent first displays |AJAX requests, starting timers|
|`componentWillReceiveProps(nextProps)`|before a component receives a new set of props|Making state transitions or making AJAX requests triggered by a changing prop|
|`shouldComponentUpdate(nextProps, nextState)`|when a re-render is due, caused by a change in state or props|Preventing unnecessary re-renders; return false to prevent the re-render, return true to allow it to continue|
|`componentWillUpdate(nextProps, nextState)`|when the component will definitely re-render|Triggering animations before a re-render|
|`render()`              |when the component needs to display something|It's mandatory!|
|`componentDidUpdate()`  |when the component has re-rendered |Triggering third-party libraries that directly manipulate the DOM|
|`componentWillUnmount()`|when the component will stop displaying|Cleaning up timers and other resources associated with the component|
|`componentDidCatch()`   |when a child of a component throws an error|Providing a clear error message to our users when something goes catastrophically wrong|

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">These methods are extremely useful when an application needs to request
data from a server. In the introduction, we pointed out that React is the View
layer, of the MVC concept, and when the client-side (View) needs to request or
send data to server-side, these lifecycle methods really do a big difference.
Let’s finish our example application, so then we can use some of the above
methods and see them in action.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: black;">We need to start by checking out
the next branch:</span><span style="color: black;"> </span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent:36.0pt"><span style="font-size:10.5pt;
font-family:Menlo;color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;background:#E7E6E6;
mso-shading-themecolor:background2;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">git checkout new-components</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">Both </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Layout</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> and </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Trello</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> components
received new code. Let’s start with </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Layout</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">:<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">In our </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Layout</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> component we
can see that we flushed the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:
10.5pt"><code>state</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;
mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> from </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:
10.5pt"><code>comments</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;
mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> and set it to an empty </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Array</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> (<i>it would be weird if a user loads the application and finds dummy notes</i>).
Then we can find a new method called </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>add</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:
text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> which takes an argument and pushes it to </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>state</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">. This method
is invoked through </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>onClick</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> which we can
find in a new </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>button</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> in our </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>render</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> method. It’s
arbitrary where to put the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>String</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> argument, and
we can leave this empty ( </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>''</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> ) too. The
other addition to the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>render</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> method is
purely for styling purposes, in which we’ve added a new </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>div</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> tag, to wrap
our </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>mapTrello</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> method, given
a particular </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>className</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> for CSS
properties. The final snippet of code that this component received, is a <i>lifecycle method</i>, which is currently <i>commented-out</i> for specific reasons. We
need you to fire up the application (<i>there
are several ways of doing this. For simplicity’s sake, you can also
double-click the HTML document, but if you load it through a code-editor, with
Live-Server capability, you’ll be able to do changes on the fly and these will
be reflected in the browser once you save your code</i>). Running the
application as is, you should see a </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>button</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> with “Add New” in it. If you <i>uncomment</i> the lifecycle method, and
refresh your app, you’ll see that now there’s a </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Trello</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> inside the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Layout</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">. This
particular lifecycle, </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>componentDidMount</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> was invoked
automatically by React, once the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Layout</code></span></span><span style="color:black;
mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> component was appended on the
DOM. In return, this method invoked the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>add</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:
text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> method, which pushed a new </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>comment</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> to the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>state</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">, and a </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Trello</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> was rendered.</span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">The only change the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Trello</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> component
received was more or less aesthetic. If we choose to load up the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>Trello</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB"> with some
preset text in it (like “Edit Your Note”), it would be easier for the user to
click a button, wipe out the <i>default</i>
text and get focus on the </span><span class="Code"><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><code>textarea</code></span></span><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB"><br></span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color:black;mso-themecolor:text1;mso-ansi-language:
EN-GB">In the next part of this course, we’ll go over 2 important aspects:</span><span style="color: black;"> </span></p><p class="MsoNormal">

EN-GB">The first will be the build system used at Loqus (<i style="mso-bidi-font-style:
normal">so far we haven’t used any, since everything is done client-side with
just the JSXTransformer directly loaded in HTML</i>), and then we’ll cover
state-managers. As we could see, in React we can store data, but offloading
this part, makes our applications perform better through a dedicated
state-manager. Will be covering MobX to see how we can apply it in our
applications.<o:p></o:p></span></p><hr>
